# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ugie-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:ugie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:ugie-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:ugie-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:ugie-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] In 1864, the Dundee-based architectural practice Edward and Robertson won the commission to build the hospital.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] Construction began in 1868 and the hospital opened as the Ayrshire District Asylum on 28 July 1869.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] The total cost of building the 230 bed hospital was £30,000.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] Two ward wings were added in 1879, the recreation hall was extended in 1886 and the wings were extended again in 1894.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] Two villas were completed in 1899 and a separate hospital block, designed by John Bennie Wilson, was added in 1906.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] It joined the National Health Service as Glengall Hospital in 1948 and became Ailsa Hospital in 1958.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] A neurosis unit was established at Loudon House in 1968.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] Ailsa Hospital offers inpatient mental health services as well as some outpatient and community services.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] In 2016 many acute mental health wards moved from Ailsa Hospital to Woodland View, a building in the grounds of Ayrshire Central Hospital.
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] It has a 12 bedded rehabilitation ward (Lochranza) and five psychiatric wards for older adults - Croy (14 beds), Dunure (15 beds), Iona/Lewis (15 beds), Jura (15 beds) and Clonbeith (15 beds).
[src:ugie-hospital/ailsa-hospital] The hospital is also the base for older adults liaison psychiatry.
[src:ugie-hospital/argyll-and-bute-hospital] The hospital, which was designed by David Cousin, opened as the Argyll District Asylum in 1863.
[src:ugie-hospital/argyll-and-bute-hospital] It became the Argyll and Bute District Asylum in 1868.
[src:ugie-hospital/argyll-and-bute-hospital] A new block, designed by Peddie & Kinnear, (sometimes referred to as the East House) was added in 1883 and, after joining the National Health Service as the Argyll and Bute Hospital in 1948, a new 30-bed extension was added and officially opened by the Duchess of Kent in 1971.
[src:ugie-hospital/argyll-and-bute-hospital] After the introduction of Care in the Community in the early 1980s, the hospital went into a period of decline and was closed to inpatients in 2016.
[src:ugie-hospital/argyll-and-bute-hospital] The hospital closed permanently in 2017.
[src:ugie-hospital/argyll-and-bute-hospital] Although a Grade C listed property, the buildings are no longer maintained and in 2020 the 'East House', being unsafe, was demolished.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The hospital was modelled on the village system of patient care, the best example of which is the Alt-Scherbitz hospital at Schkeuditz in Germany which was developed in the 1870s.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] It was designed by Hippolyte Blanc and officially opened as the Edinburgh District Asylum in October 1906.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] At the centre of the site was an Edwardian Baroque hall.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The site also incorporated a power station, workshops, a bakery, stores, a kitchen and a laundry.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The hospital was requisitioned by the War Office during the First World War but reverted to psychiatric work between the wars.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] A Romanesque style church, designed by Harold Ogle Tarbolton, was built between 1924 and 1930.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] Temporary marquees and prefabricated huts were erected to cope with the demand for wartime bed space: the temporary facility became noted for its burns and plastic surgery unit which was established in 1940.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] After the war the temporary facility was developed as Bangour General Hospital.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] After general medical services transferred to the newly-opened St John's Hospital in nearby Livingston, Bangour General Hospital closed in 1991.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The Village Hospital also started to wind down after the opening of St Johns with the last remaining ward closing in 2004.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The closed hospital was used as a filming location for the 2005 film *The Jacket*, starring Keira Knightley and Adrien Brody.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] During September 2009, the hospital grounds were used as the site for "Exercise Green Gate", a counter-terrorist exercise run by the Scottish Government to test de-contamination procedures in the event of a nuclear, chemical or biological incident.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] This involved 250 volunteer "casualties" and 400 emergency staff.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] On 1 October 2015, planning permission for a residential and mixed use redevelopment of the former hospital site was sought under the new settlement name 'Bangour Village'.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The application noted some of the listed buildings would require full demolition in a subsequent application, including villas 7,8,9 and 21, with other buildings potentially proposed for partial demolition.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] In early 2020, it was confirmed that five of the listed buildings on site were in very poor condition and were planned to be demolished, while the remaining ten buildings were due to be redeveloped for housing.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The first permission in principle for the development was given in March 2021 which allowed Allanwater Developments (Bangour) Ltd (then owners) to demolish 4 Category C listed buildings and partially demolish the B listed nurses' home.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The plans also included provision for a district heating system, a new village shop and a new primary school (incorporating the Category A listed recreation hall).
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] While some demolition took place, construction was delayed.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] In April 2024, RoundShield (an investment company) and the Ambassador Group (estate agents) announced that they had secured funding of £21 million for a large-scale residential development on the site.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] This would initially include 51 "energy-efficient" new homes and the first 23 refurbished flats within the existing listed buildings, with 998 homes planned in total.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The two companies also announced the sale of part of the site to Barratt Homes for further residential development.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The subsequent plans saw a proposal for 395 houses and 82 flats as well as the conversion of listed buildings in the form of another 63 flats.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] The planning process decision was delayed in October 2024.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] However, in November 2024, the final plans for the Bangour Village estate were approved by West Lothian Council, with 976 of the planned homes approved.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] In January 2025, Barratt Redrow commenced construction of the new properties, with the first new homes becoming available in September 2025.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] When the hospital was built, road access was poor, and considerable volumes of coal and general stores were required for the running of the facility.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] A private railway line was built, branching from the former Edinburgh and Bathgate Railway line at Uphall, and terminating at Bangour railway station.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] It was authorised by the Edinburgh and District Lunacy Board Act of 30 July 1900, and it was opened to passengers on 19 June 1905.
[src:ugie-hospital/bangour-village-hospital] During the First World War the road network was improved, and the railway became unnecessary; it was closed on 1 August 1921, although passenger services probably ceased on 4 May 1921.
[src:ugie-hospital/ugie-hospital] The foundation stone for the facility was laid in June 1905.
[src:ugie-hospital/ugie-hospital] It first opened as the local infectious diseases hospital in 1907.
[src:ugie-hospital/ugie-hospital] In 2004, the Ravenscraig geriatric ward at the hospital was closed to new admissions because of an outbreak of MRSA among the elderly patients.
[src:ugie-hospital/ugie-hospital] Eight of the 13 patients were found to be carriers of the bacteria, although none of the patients was actually infected.
[src:ugie-hospital/ugie-hospital] After certain services transferred to Fraserburgh Hospital, the Buchanhaven Ward at Ugie Hospital was closed in May 2011.
